{{Refimprove|date=June 2011}}
{{Vietnamese name|Lý|Tường}}
'''Lý Long Tường''' ({{linktext|李|龍|祥}}; 1174–?) was a prince of the [[Lý Dynasty]] of [[Đại Việt]] (in modern-day [[Vietnam]]) and later became '''Lee Yong-sang''' (이용상) of Hwasan, a general of Korea. He is an ancestor of one branch of the [[Lee (Korean surname)|Lee]] (or Rhee) family today in both South and North Korea.<ref>Phillip Taylor, Modernity and Re-Enchantment: Religion in Post-Revolutionary Vietnam  Institute of Southeast Asian Studies - 2007 - Page 80 "To this day, the Lý Long Tường branch of the Vietnamese royal family is concentrated in the Hoa Son district outside of Seoul in what is now South Korea (Phạm Côn Sơn 1998). In the 1980s, one descendant of this wayward prince began ..."</ref> 

Lý was born in 1174, the seventh son of Emperor [[Lý Anh Tông]] (who reigned from 1138–75) and his consort Le My Nga. He was appointed the Great National Tutor.<ref>{{lang-vi|Thái sư Thương trụ quốc, Khai phủ nghị đồng tam tư, Thượng thư tả bộc xạ, lĩnh đại đô đốc, tước Kiến Bình vương}}</ref>

In 1225, [[Trần Thủ Độ]] overthrew the Lý Dynasty by introducing his nephew [[Trần Cảnh]] to the imperial court to serve the incumbent Empress [[Lý Chiêu Hoàng]], he then orchestrated a political marriage between Trần Cảnh and Lý Chiêu Hoàng and thereafter forced Lý Chiêu Hoàng to abdicate in favour of her husband Trần Cảnh. This marked the end of the Lý Dynasty and the beginning of the Trần Dynasty. With the Trần family having just gained the throne, Trần Thủ Độ ordered the massacre of the Lý family members and forced all of its descendants to change their surname to Nguyen, and sent them to the northern mountainous areas.

==Life in exile==
{{Unreferenced section|date=June 2011}}
In 1226, (Kien Trung's year of the Second Trần Dynasty of Thai Tong), in order to avoid further bloodshed by the Trần family, Lý Long Tường, together with 6000 [[Mandarin (bureaucrat)|mandarin]]s and servants departed from the Than Phu (now [[Thanh Hóa Province]]) estuary and fled to the [[South China Sea]] in three large ships. They carried relics with them, including the imperial crown, imperial costumes, and the heaven imperial sword ({{lang|vi|Thượng phương bảo kiếm}}). After a month on the high seas, they were forced to land in [[Taiwan]] due to a typhoon. When Lý Long Tường decided to leave, his son Ly Long Hien was severely ill and had to stay in Taiwan together with 200 mandarins, followers and servants. Lý Long Tường continued northwards to [[Ongjin County, South Hwanghae|Ongjin County]] and then on to [[Haeju]], [[Hwanghae]] in the [[Yellow Sea]]. Legend has it that the Korean king [[Gojong of Goryeo|Kojong]] of the [[Goryeo]] Dynasty (1192–1259) had dreamt of a grand [[Phoenix (mythology)|phoenix]] flying from the south and landing in his nation. Therefore, he ordered the local government of Hae-ju to give the Vietnamese royal refugees a red-carpeted welcome and allow them to live in a manor in his country.

Lý Long Tường and his companions started their culture of fishing and breeding. He also opened a school for literature (poetry, rhythmical prose and worship rituals) and a school to teach martial arts - the art of war. Thousands of local students joined his two schools.

==Defeat of the Mongol invaders==
In 1232, an army of the [[Mongol Empire]] led by [[General Sartai]] launched an [[Mongol invasion of Korea|attack on Korea]] by both sea and land. The troops, using the waterways, attacked Hwang-hae but were defeated by the army and the local inhabitants led by Ly Long Tuong.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} Ly Long Tuong always rode a white horse and as a result, was dubbed the "White Horse General."{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}

In 1253, the Mongol army led by the great Khan [[Möngke Khan|Möngke]] launched a second attack on Korea. The Yuan-Mongol army, led by Tang Ji, attacked Hwang-hae overland and by using the waterways. Lý Long Tường, although by then over 70 years old, led the army and the local inhabitants to victory after a five-month campaign.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} As a result of this important triumph, the Korean king renamed Jin-san ({{korean=진산|hanja=鎭山}}) Hwa-san ({{korean=화산|hanja=花山}}) and appointed Ly Long Tuong Hwa-san gun (花山君). The location of the Mongol army surrender was called the Gate of Surrender Acceptance ({{lang|ko-Hani|{{linktext|受|降|門}}}}; ''Su-hang-mun''). The Korean king also had a pillar erected here to honour Ly Long Tuong. (The pillar can still be seen today).{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}

When Lý Long Tường died, he was buried at the foot of Mount Di A near Panmunjeom ({{lang|ko-Hani|板門店}}).{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} The mountain peak (Kwang-dea) where Lý Long Tường always sat to look southwards and cried is now called the "Peak of Nostalgia" ({{lang|ko-Hani|{{linktext|望|國|壇}}}}).

==Descendants in Korea==
Today, there are some 1500 households in [[North Korea]] and 600 in [[South Korea]] with connections to Lý Long Tường.<ref>''Korea's Changing Roles in Southeast Asia: Expanding Influence and ...'' - Page 34 David I. Steinberg, ed. - 2010 "... of the Vietnamese Ly prince, called Ly Long Tuong, who led the exile could be around 1,500 (Viet Nam News). ".</ref> A descendant of Lý Long Tường, Lee Chang Kun (Ly Xuong Can), and Ly Sang Joon (Ly Tung Tuan, the Founder of [[Golden Bridge Finance Group]]) visits Lý's temple in Dinh Bang village in Bắc Ninh Province every year with his family living and sends money to help in the reconstruction of the temple. He has also invested in local projects and together with this family took up Vietnamese citizenship in 2010. His son born in 1997 was named Ly Viet Quoc.<ref>[http://nld.com.vn/20100629122620558p0c1002/dat-to-mai-trong-tim.htm Dat to mai trong con tim]</ref> At the end of 1995, a report on Lý Long Tường was broadcast by South Korean TV channel [[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS]].{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}

Also, Lý Long Tường is the founder of one of the [[Korean clan]], [[Hwasan Lee clan]].<ref>{{Cite book|author=|date=|title=Academy of Korean Studies 화산이씨 花山李氏|publisher=[[Academy of Korean Studies]]|url=http://terms.naver.com/entry.nhn?docId=291465&cid=42835&categoryId=42835&mobile}}</ref>

