{{Infobox recurring event |name = Pennsylvania Renaissance Faire |image = Parenfairelogo.jpg |alt = |caption = |location = [[Rapho Township, Lancaster County, Pennsylvania]], [[Lancaster County, Pennsylvania|Lancaster County]], [[Pennsylvania]] |genre = Renaissance fair |first = 1981 |dates = August – October |attendance = 250,000<ref name="Consuming History">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hexpdOj8t80C&pg=PA120&dq=%22Pennsylvania+Renaissance+Faire%22+-inpublisher:icon&as_brr=0&ei=l3V4SsvHAaWSywTYxLmSAw#v=onepage&q=%22Pennsylvania%20Renaissance%20Faire%22%20-inpublisher%3Aicon&f=false |title=Consuming History |last=De Groot |first=Jerome |year=2008 |publisher=Taylor & Francis |page=120 |ISBN=0-415-39945-9}}</ref> (average) |area = {{convert|35|acre|m2}} |free_label = Stages |free_text = 15 |website = {{url|http://www.parenfaire.com/faire/index.php|parenfaire.com/faire/}} }} The '''Pennsylvania Renaissance Faire''' is a [[Renaissance fair]] occurring over 13 weekends from early-August through late-October on the grounds of the [[Mount Hope Estate and Winery]] in [[Manheim Township, Lancaster County, Pennsylvania|Manheim, Pennsylvania]].<ref name="Odesser-Torpey">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DR7mhJY5FjwC&pg=PA222&dq=%22Pennsylvania+Renaissance+Faire%22+-inpublisher:icon&as_brr=0&ei=ZmZ4SslWi5LKBJnG7IYD#v=onepage&q=%22Pennsylvania%20Renaissance%20Faire%22%20-inpublisher%3Aicon&f=false |title=Insiders' Guide to Pennsylvania Dutch Country| last=Odesser-Torpey |first=Marilyn |ISBN=0-7627-4786-2 |publisher=Globe Pequot |year=2008 |pages=222 to 223}}</ref> In 1980, the Estate was sold and converted to a winery.
==History==
In 1980, a two-day jousting festival called the Pennsylvania Renaissance Faire was held in the winery parking lot to attract visitors. The event proved popular, and expanded in the following years.<ref name="business">{{cite web |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa5295/is_199807/ai_n24335724/ |title=Period fun at the Renaissance Faire doth maketh the bottom line strong |publisher=Central Penn Business Journal |date=1998-07-03 |accessdate=2009-08-05}}</ref>
In 2009, the Faire was held on a {{convert|35|acre|m2|adj=on}} site with 90 shows performed daily on 12 stages, hundreds of costumed characters, and a recreation of a 16th-century English village with authentic Tudor buildings. Musical performances, Shakespearean plays, and other acts were offered, twenty-three "Royal Kitchens" served food and drink, and Renaissance merchants were on-site.<ref name="PA DCED">{{cite web |url=http://visitpa.com/things-to-do/event-calendar/event-details/index.aspx?id=21306460 |title=29th Annual Pennsylvania Renaissance Faire |publisher=Pennsylvania Department of Community and Economic Development |accessdate=2009-08-05}}</ref> The Swashbuckler Brewing Company was founded on the grounds in 2000,<ref name="Penn Brew">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=95Yluit6hgMC&pg=PA121&lpg=PA121&dq=romito+bowser&source=bl&ots=Z21Of0KSiB&sig=L0VefHjubkeY7noUA8zoUkl7U-Y&hl=en&ei=Ml94Ss3qCNSvtgeHodSWCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1#v=onepage&q=romito%20bowser&f=false |title=Pennsylvania Breweries |last=Bryson |first=Lew |publisher=Stackpole Books |year=2005 |ISBN=0-8117-3222-3 |pages=121 to 124}}</ref> and its product is available at the Swashbuckler Brew Pub.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parenfaire.com/pages/swashbuckler_brewery/swashbuckler_history.html |title=Swashbuckler History |publisher=Swashbuckler Brewing Company |accessdate=2009-08-23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090608190142/http://www.parenfaire.com/pages/swashbuckler_brewery/swashbuckler_history.html |archivedate=June 8, 2009 }}</ref>
==Praise==
The Faire's music and storytelling have been praised by the [[Pennsylvania Department of Conservation and Natural Resources]] Little Buffalo Performance Center, and, in 1998, the Faire was named one of the top 100 motorcoach-accessible events in America by the American Bus Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collegian.psu.edu/archive/2000/09/09-08-00tdc/09-08-00darts-6.asp |last=Neville |first=Erin |work=The Daily Collegian |title=Pennsylvania Renaissance Faire an educational experience out of class |date=2000-09-08 |accessdate=2009-08-04 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060904062821/http://www.collegian.psu.edu/archive/2000/09/09-08-00tdc/09-08-00darts-6.asp |archivedate=2006-09-04 |df= }}</ref>
==Business==
As a privately owned business, the faire is not required to report revenues to the public. In a 1998 interview, the owner, Chuck Romito, revealed that "Gross sales for wine purchases and tickets for shows at the Mount Hope Estates--including Christmas, Halloween, Roaring '20s and other theme performances--hover around $4 million," while the faire's expenses were about $2 million.<ref name="business" />
As of 2008, American Renaissance festivals were much larger in scale than their European counterparts. ''Consuming History'' specifically mentions the Pennsylvania Renaissance Faire for its high attendance, along with the [[Maryland Renaissance Festival|Maryland Renaissance Faire]], which draws 225,000 visitors over three weeks, and the [[Bristol Renaissance Faire]], which reached a peak in 1990 with 400,000 visitors in seven weekends.<ref name="Consuming History" />
