{{Other uses|Lilac Festival (disambiguation){{!}}Lilac Festival}} [[Image:LilacFestival 2005.JPG|thumb|300px|Lilac Festival 2005 at the Highland Park]]
The '''Rochester Lilac Festival''' is an art, music, food and flora festival hosted annually in early May in [[Highland Park (Rochester, New York)|Highland Park]] in [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]], [[New York State|New York]]. Highland Park possesses a huge collection of [[lilac]]s, featuring more than 1800 bushes and over 500 different varieties.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rochester Lilac Festival|url=http://www.rochesterevents.com/festivals-events/lilac-festival/highland-park-gardens|website=Rochester Events|accessdate=April 4, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130501235923/http://www.rochesterevents.com/festivals-events/lilac-festival/highland-park-gardens|archivedate=May 1, 2013}}</ref>
The festival is started with a parade and frequently hosts concerts and other attractions during the week. The [[Highland Park (Rochester, New York)|Highland Park]] [[arboretum]] is toured free of charge and is open to all visitors. The fields surrounding the arboretum host a myriad of vendor's tents and food stands. The festival ends each year with the annual Lilac 10K road race and 5K Family Fun Run. The 10K Course is USATF certified.
==History== In 1888, nurserymen [[George Ellwanger]] and [[Patrick Barry (horticulture)|Patrick Barry]] endowed the Rochester community with {{convert|20|acre|m2}} of gently rolling hills that are now known as [[Highland Park, Rochester, New York|Highland Park]].<ref name="D&C_May2009">{{cite web |url=http://www.democratandchronicle.com/article/20090507/LIVING/905070334/-1/specials46/Ellwanger+and+Barry+gift+has+lasted+more+than+a+century |title=Ellwanger and Barry gift has lasted more than a century |newspaper=Rochester Democrat & Chronicle |date=May 7, 2009 |author= |accessdate=April 3, 2015}}</ref> It was noted as one of the nation's first municipal arboretums. Renowned park designer [[Frederick Law Olmsted]] was responsible for final development of Highland Park. The park's lilac collection was started by horticulturist John Dunbar in 1892 with 20 varieties, some of which were descendants of slips of native Balkan Mountain flowers that were carried to the new world by early colonists. Today, over 500 varieties of lilacs cover 22 of Highland Park's {{convert|155|acre|km2}}.
The inspiration for the festival dates to 1898 when 3,000 people came to the park one Sunday in May to see the lilacs. Ten years later, 25,000 people came to the first organized lilac festival.<ref name="D&C_May2009"/> Since then the number of viewers has grown to over 500,000 and the festival plays out over the course of ten days.
